  sum += grade;

  if(grade > max) {
    max = grade;  
  }

  if(grade < min) {
    min = grade;
  }
}
```

This calculates the sum, min, and max by looping through the grades.

So in summary, the main loop is a while loop to display the menu, and it uses for loops to process the grades data stored in the ArrayList.

Yes, we can modify the program to associate student names with each grade. Here are the changes needed:

1. Instead of just storing grades in the ArrayList, we can create a Student class:

```java 
class Student {
  String name;
  double grade;

  Student(String name, double grade) {
    this.name = name;
    this.grade = grade;
  }
}
```

2. Update the grades ArrayList to store Students rather than just doubles:

```java
private static ArrayList<Student> students = new ArrayList<>(); 
```

3. When adding a grade, also ask for the student's name:

```java
private static void addGrade() {
  Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);
  System.out.print("Enter student name: ");
  String name = sc.nextLine();

  System.out.print("Enter grade: ");
  double grade = sc.nextDouble();

  students.add(new Student(name, grade));
} 
```

4. When displaying grades or generating reports, print the name as well:

```java
private static void displayGrades() {
  // loop through students ArrayList
  System.out.println(student.name + ": " + student.grade); 
}
```

This allows associating names with each grade entered. Let me know if you need any clarification or have additional questions!

Yes, we can implement this using ArrayLists instead of a custom Student class. Here is how:

1. Create two ArrayLists - one to store student names and one to store grades:

```java
private static ArrayList<String> studentNames = new ArrayList<>();
private static ArrayList<Double> grades = new ArrayList<>();
```

2. When adding a grade, also ask for and store the student name:

```java 
private static void addGrade() {
  Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);

  System.out.print("Enter student name: ");
  String name = sc.nextLine();
  studentNames.add(name);

  System.out.print("Enter grade: ");
  double grade = sc.nextDouble();
  grades.add(grade);
}
```

3. When displaying grades or generating reports, loop through both arrays:

```java
for(int i=0; i<studentNames.size(); i++) {
  System.out.println(studentNames.get(i) + ": " + grades.get(i));
}
```

This associates each grade with a student by storing them at the same index in two separate ArrayLists.

The advantage of using a custom Student class is that it keeps the student name and grade together. But this ArrayList approach works too and avoids creating a custom class.

